<h1>2.3.2 2nd declension</h1>
<h2 id="relevant-postag-codes">Relevant postag codes:</h2>
<p><strong>Position and letters in postag string:</strong></p>
<ol type="1">
<li><p>part of speech: <strong>1st</strong>; letter: <strong>n</strong>
(noun)</p></li>
<li><p>number: <strong>3rd</strong>; letters: <strong>s</strong>
(singular), <strong>d</strong> (dual), <strong>p</strong>
(plural)</p></li>
<li><p>gender: <strong>7th</strong>; letters: <strong>m</strong>
(masculine), <strong>f</strong> (feminine), <strong>n</strong>
(neuter)</p></li>
<li><p>case: <strong>8th</strong>; letters: <strong>n</strong>
(nominative), <strong>g</strong> (genitive), <strong>d</strong>
(dative), <strong>a</strong> (accusative), <strong>v</strong>
(vocative)</p></li>
</ol>
<p><strong>Example postag string:</strong> n-s—mn- (noun, singular,
masculine, nominative)</p>
<h2 id="summary">Summary</h2>
<p>Nouns in AG are usually treated as inflecting in three
<strong>declensions</strong>. The declensions have their own sets of
endings.</p>
<p>The second declension, also called as o-declension, includes mostly
masculine words that end in the nominative singular in -ος or -ους and
neuter nouns ending in -ον (or -ουν). For the 2nd declension tables in
classical Attic Greek, endings here
<a data-link-newtab="" href="/smyth/body.1_div1.2_div2.4.html+body.1_div1.2_div2.4_div3.2" data-url="smyth/body.1_div1.2_div2.4.html+body.1_div1.2_div2.4_div3.2">see Smyth
§228</a>.</p>
<h2 id="examples-of-inflection-from-papygreek-corpus">Examples of
inflection from PapyGreek corpus</h2>
<h3 id="nd-declension">2nd declension</h3>
<ol type="1">
<li>Masculine nouns ending in nominative singular in -ος or -ους,
e.g.</li>
</ol>
<ul>
<li>ὁ δοῦλος (ho doûlos) <em>slave</em> <a data-link-newtab="" href="/search/7" data-url="search/7">search all forms of
this lemma</a></li>
<li>ὁ νόος (ho nóos) <em>mind</em> (Attic contraction νοῦς)
<a data-link-newtab="" href="/search/12" data-url="search/12">search all forms of this lemma</a></li>
</ul>
<ol start="2" type="1">
<li>Feminine nouns ending in in nominative singular in -ος, e.g.</li>
</ol>
<ul>
<li>ἡ νόσος (ho nósos) <em>disease</em> <a data-link-newtab="" href="/search/10" data-url="search/10">search all forms of
this lemma</a></li>
</ul>
<ol start="3" type="1">
<li>Neuter nouns ending in nominative singular in -ον (or -ουν),
e.g.</li>
</ol>
<ul>
<li>τὸ ἱμάτιον (tò himátion) <em>dress, cloth</em> <a data-link-newtab="" href="/search/11" data-url="search/11">search all
forms of this lemma</a></li>
</ul>
<ol start="4" type="1">
<li>Attic declension, e.g.&nbsp;ὁ νεώς (ho néōs) for ὁ ναός (ho nāos) or ὁ
λεώς (ho leôs) for ὁ λαός (ho lāos)
<a data-link-newtab="" href="/smyth/body.1_div1.2_div2.4.html+body.1_div1.2_div2.4_div3.4" data-url="smyth/body.1_div1.2_div2.4.html+body.1_div1.2_div2.4_div3.4">see
Smyth</a>, was not adopted in the Koine (<span class="citation" data-cites="emde2019">Emde Boas et al. (2019)</span>), and does not
appear in papyri</li>
</ol>
<ul>
<li>ὁ ναός (ho nāos) <em>temple</em> <a data-link-newtab="" href="/search/13" data-url="search/13">search all forms of this
lemma</a></li>
<li>ὁ λαός (ho lāos) <em>people</em> <a data-link-newtab="" href="/search/14" data-url="search/14">search all forms of this
lemma</a></li>
</ul>
